Configuration Management Policy – Kahana Oasis

Owner: DevOps / Engineering Lead
Approved By: CTO
Effective Date: March 2026

1. Purpose
This policy establishes requirements for baseline configurations, hardening standards, configuration changes (including approvals and testing), use of infrastructure-as-code, and detection/remediation of configuration drift for Kahana Oasis systems.

2. Scope
Applies to all production and staging infrastructure for Kahana Oasis, including AWS (us-east-1), Supabase, Lambda, Terraform definitions, CI/CD (GitHub workflows), and application configuration.

3. Infrastructure as Code (IaC)
Kahana uses Terraform for AWS infrastructure and GitHub for application code. All infrastructure changes must be version-controlled and reviewed via pull requests. Configuration values that are secrets (API keys, tokens) must be stored in AWS Secrets Manager, not in code.

4. Baseline and Hardening
Production systems must follow security baselines: encryption at rest and in transit (Supabase, TLS); least-privilege IAM; security groups and network segmentation per design. Supabase and AWS default security configurations must be verified and hardened where needed.

5. Configuration Change Process
Configuration changes follow the Change Management Policy: tracked via GitHub PRs, peer-reviewed, tested in non-production before production deployment. High-risk changes (IAM, security groups, database settings) require explicit approval from Engineering Lead or DevOps.

6. Configuration Drift
Periodic reviews (manual or automated) should detect configuration drift. Deviations from IaC definitions must be documented, justified, or reverted. Gaps identified are tracked in the Risk Register.

7. Review and Maintenance
This policy is reviewed at least annually. Updates require approval from the policy owner and CTO.
